Emergency powers were folded into this expansion. A classified memo from the Justice Department\'92s Office of Legal Counsel surfaced, justifying lethal boat strikes in the Caribbean as collective self-defense that did not require congressional approval. The strikes had already killed 83 people on vessels the United States claimed were tied to drug trafficking, though no drugs were found and survivors were not charged. The memo\'92s logic was simple and sweeping: if the executive deemed an action in the national interest and not \'93prolonged,\'94 it could proceed without Congress. At the same time, the administration invoked a \'93national energy emergency\'94 to force a Michigan coal plant to remain open despite retirement plans, shifting roughly $113 million in costs onto ratepayers across the Midwest. Emergency language, once reserved for rare crises, became a routine tool to bypass state policy, environmental concerns, and legislative debate. It became a habit, not an exception.\
