If executive power was stretching outward, law itself was bending inward, away from limit and toward weapon. The Justice Department was at the center of this shift. Reports described a purge of roughly 5,500 DOJ employees since Trump\'92s return to office, including many who had prosecuted the January 6 attack. The civil rights division had lost 70% of its staff. The public integrity section, once the engine of federal corruption cases, had been reduced from about 30 lawyers to two. At the same time, the voting section\'92s mission had been realigned with Trump\'92s electoral agenda, backing a Texas redistricting plan that favored Republicans while attacking a California plan that aided Democrats. Law enforcement resources were not simply thinner; they were redirected, away from corruption and civil rights and toward immigration crackdowns and partisan fights. Capacity was hollowed out where it might check power and reinforced where it could serve it.\
