The Comey and Letitia James prosecutions showed how this weaponization worked in practice\'97and how courts could still resist. Lindsey Halligan, a novice prosecutor appointed as interim U.S. attorney, had indicted former FBI Director James Comey and New York Attorney General Letitia James on charges widely seen as retaliatory. A federal judge, Cameron McGowan Currie, dismissed both cases after finding that Halligan\'92s appointment was unlawful and unconstitutional. The indictments, she ruled, were void because the prosecutor herself had no legal authority. Attorney General Pam Bondi vowed to appeal, but the damage to DOJ\'92s credibility was already done. The same week, a conservative appeals court upheld nearly $1 million in sanctions against Trump and his lawyer Alina Habba for a frivolous racketeering suit against Hillary Clinton and others, noting a \'93pattern\'94 of meritless litigation. These rulings did not restore a neutral Justice Department, but they showed that some judges were still willing to draw lines. The bench had not gone silent.\
