The pardon power became another channel for that expectation. Trump had already issued a broad pardon on November 7 that, by its language, might cover any U.S. citizen involved in voter fraud during the 2020 election. Legal experts warned that it could shield a wide range of actors, from fake electors to individuals who voted in two states. In Week 45, he announced his intention to grant a full pardon to Juan Orlando Hern\'e1ndez, the former president of Honduras serving a 45-year sentence in the United States for drug trafficking and weapons charges. Trump claimed Hern\'e1ndez had been treated unfairly. The move signaled that even foreign leaders convicted of major crimes could expect mercy if their cases fit the president\'92s narrative. Law, in this frame, was not a neutral boundary but a field of exceptions, drawn around those close to power. Impunity became a perk of proximity.\
